 and primary and secondary instrumentalisation. Identifying the limitations resulting from Feenberg's attachment to critique, the book offers a utopian corrective that can provide a fuller account of the process of willed technological transformation and of the author's own idea of a technologically authorised socialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAdorno.  aCritical Theory.  aDesign.  aFeenberg.  aFoucault.  aMarx.  aPhilosophy.  aRadical democracy.  aTechnology.  aUtopia.1 aKirkpatrick, Graeme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526105349zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526105349zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526105349/original  a978-3-11-128248-0 Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA